I often think that the millennium generation may be the last generation that can purely appreciate art and establish a connection with artists. They don't have that pressure, and don't need to wear critical, colored glasses to scrutinize everything.
We grew up in the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of popular culture, but now, this collective consciousness has disappeared.
Back then, we didn't need to consider the source of the content; we could directly immerse ourselves in it, because in that era, tracing the roots was not easy.
We revered these artists as gods, and we also didn't have any reason to question this reverence. Thus, we established a kind of "pseudo-social relationship" with them and regarded it as an indispensable part of life.
This also explains why we are so fond of nostalgia.
The Office was still on air when I'd gather with my friends every Thursday, eating pizza while watching the show.
This experience is vastly different from how we consume media today with streaming platforms. They usually release 12 episodes at once, and everyone watches at their own pace, posting about the plot on social media while warning of spoilers, or discussing it in specific groups.
Deep down, we all yearn for that collective sense of belonging that's linked everyone together.
It's this nostalgia that drives us to rewatch The Office and similar TV series or movies like Anchorman, where those iconic lines are passed around like memes on the internet.
We'd quote those iconic lines from these works and assume that most people would understand the reference.
As if something goes viral online, we can't assume everyone has seen it.
With the explosion of information, there's just too much to pay attention to... Do we have a chance to break free from this information overload?
We keep discovering new media and artists, only to find out they're either notorious sex offenders or spewing biases as die-hard fanatics, and it just gets exhausting.
On one hand, we're indulging in nostalgia; on the other hand, we have to acknowledge that the creators of our beloved art might have severe moral flaws, leaving us lost for what to do.
We'll be more cautious about establishing a "pseudo-social relationship" with artists.
We gradually realize that, in order to acquire wealth and power, it's hard to ensure oneself won't harm or exploit others.
Due to the disappearance of the collective consciousness of the media, we have formed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, there are also some people who remain obstinate and insist on putting others on a pedestal, only to pretend to be shocked when their idols fall.
We are in a time of revolution, and I urgently want to know where we are headed.
